body:
Would you disable memory pattern and try it again?
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/include/onnxruntime/core/session/onnxruntime_c_api.h#L223

I tried it with the Python binding by specifying session option when loading the model, but the same error occurred when I ran the model.
```Python
session_option = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
session_option.enable_mem_pattern = False
decoder = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(decoder_path, session_option)
```
@guanluo is this still an issue with the latest 1.0 release?
I will verify it as soon as possible.

> @GuanLuo is this still an issue with the latest 1.0 release?

I am running into the same issue with ARM32.  onnxruntime is running on  on raspberry pi edge device module container following this example. 
[YOLOv3 Object Detection on RPi 3 with Azure IoT Edge](https://github.com/microsoft/azure-iot-edge-cv-model-samples/tree/master/IoT/Rpi3-objectdetection)
Opened an  [issue](https://github.com/microsoft/azure-iot-edge-cv-model-samples/issues) in there.
 
I was thinking that this is  due to ARM32  setup and the device maybe under powered. But looks like its actually within onnxruntime regardless the arm architecture.
@faxu unfortunately the OOM is still happening in 1.0.0 release
@GuanLuo I assume you are using sequential executor?
@yuslepukhin I believe so since the two models are encoder and decoder

Can you also try disabling the memory arena by calling OrtApi::DisableCpuMemArena? If that and memory pattern are disabled ORT will just call malloc/free for each individual request instead of maintaining it's own buffers/cache in an attempt to minimize allocations. If it still runs out of memory with that setup the model requires more memory than you have available, and the next question would be whether particular operator implementations could be more efficient. 

Note: There's currently no way to disable arena usage on GPU, so please test this on CPU only.

Hi @GuonLuo,

Does this issue still persist ? If so is the model shareable ? I think this maybe a bad model conversion if it is requesting so much memory - something along the lines of what was happening here - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2699
@hariharans29  Yes the issue still exists... You can obtain the models here: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1dSaB-PjmIuugPaln5cpSqwfNz8re_Nex/view?usp=sharing
